nks":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1808"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1808"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64396"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"355"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1258"},{"type":"tags","id":"3424"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11234"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35192"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79044"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department a 12-hour history of vomiting and an inability to keep any liquids down. Prior to this, she has had increasing early satiety and regurgitation over the last four months. She has a medical history of angina, for which two drug-eluting coronary artery stents were inserted two years ago. Her medications include rivaroxaban and aspirin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination she appears well. She has a pulse rate of 100/min and blood pressure 140/80 mmHg. A nasogastric tube is inserted and drains 500 ml of gastric secretions. After this the patients feels much more comfortable. A chest X-ray shows a large para-oesophageal hernia with a fluid level and the nasogastric tube coiled up above the diaphragm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate laparoscopic reduction and repair of the obstructed hernia","Stop the rivaroxaban with a view to surgery in two day\u0027s time","Immediate percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy","Fresh frozen plasma and proceed to surgery","Prothrombin and proceed to surgery"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient will require surgical intervention to deal with what is, in effect, a gastric volvulus. In other words, the para-oesophageal hernia has twisted and become obstructed. This would explain her vomiting and the inability of the nasogastric tube to pass in to the distal stomach. The stomach has now been partially decompressed and surgery can now wait until decisions are made on how to manage her anticoagulants. The balance between risks of a further cardiac event and increased operative bleeding must be weighed up. In this case she would be at serious risk of a further cardiac event if the aspirin was stopped. The planned operation would be  a laparoscopic reduction and repair of her para-oesophageal hernia- a relatively safe procedure from the bleeding risk point of view. It would probably be quite appropriate to continue the aspirin and a cardiological opinion should be sought. The \u003Cstrong\u003Erivaroxaban should be stopped\u003C/strong\u003E and surgery delayed until the effects of the factor Xa inhibitor have worn off. Rivaroxaban has a half life of 7 - 13 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgery (a \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopic reduction\u003C/strong\u003E and repair of her para-oesophageal hernia) can now be done on a semi-urgent basis and there is no need to give \u003Cstrong\u003Eprothrombin\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Efresh frozen plasma\u003C/strong\u003E. These agents might be considered if urgent surgical intervention was required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the patient was a poor surgical risk, a \u003Cstrong\u003Epercutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered as a way of anchoring the decompressed stomach back in the abdominal cavity. However, that approach is unlikely to be needed in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Where possible, rivaroxaban and similar agents should be stopped before any major surgical procedure."],"references":["Sunkara T, Ofori E, Zarubin V, et al. Perioperative Management of Direct Oral Anticoagulants (DOACs): A Systemic Review. Health Services Insights 2016; 9:25-36. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28008269/","Chassot PG, Marcucci C, Delabays A. Perioperative Antiplatelet Therapy. Am Fam Physician. 2010;82:1484-89. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21166368/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64396"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1808"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64396"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T13:50:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T13:06:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1808"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79044"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emer